        <div class="dose-cell"><div class="dose-cell-label">Clinical Studies</div><div class="dose-cell-value">1,000 to 3,000 mg</div></div>
        <div class="dose-cell"><div class="dose-cell-label">Typical Supplement</div><div class="dose-cell-value">500 mg</div></div>
        <div class="dose-cell highlight"><div class="dose-cell-label">DayShift</div><div class="dose-cell-value">2,500 mg</div></div>
      </div>
      <p class="dose-note">DayShift dose is a 2,500 mg equivalent from an 8:1 concentrated fruiting body extract.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="learn">
      <h2>Want to Learn More?</h2>
      <p class="learn-intro">Explore the peer-reviewed research on Lion's Mane (<em>Hericium erinaceus</em>) and cognitive function.</p>
      <div class="study-grid">
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37999903/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">RCT &middot; Nutrients, 2023</div><div class="study-title">Acute and chronic effects of Lion's Mane on cognition in healthy adults</div><p class="study-desc">A single serving of Lion's Mane was associated with improved mental processing speed in healthy adults within an hour, with continued effects over 28 days.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18844328/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">RCT &middot; Phytotherapy Research, 2009</div><div class="study-title">Improving effects of Lion's Mane on mild cognitive impairment</div><p class="study-desc">Mori et al. Adults taking Lion's Mane daily for 16 weeks scored higher on cognitive function tests than the placebo group, with improvements building over time.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20834180/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">RCT &middot; Biomedical Research, 2010</div><div class="study-title">Lion's Mane and reduction of depression and anxiety</div><p class="study-desc">Nagano et al. Daily Lion's Mane for four weeks was associated with reductions in self-reported anxiety and irritability versus placebo, suggesting benefits beyond cognition.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23735479/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">Review &middot; Int. J. Med. Mushrooms, 2013</div><div class="study-title">Neurotrophic properties of Lion's Mane compounds</div><p class="study-desc">A review of how hericenones and erinacines, the bioactive compounds in Lion's Mane, support Nerve Growth Factor activity and neuronal health.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31413233/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">Review &middot; Biomolecules, 2019</div><div class="study-title">Bioactive compounds in Lion's Mane and brain health</div><p class="study-desc">An overview of the neuroprotective and cognitive-supporting compounds in Lion's Mane, including their roles in neurogenesis, NGF, and oxidative balance.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="study" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33549965/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div class="study-meta">Review &middot; Antioxidants, 2021</div><div class="study-title">Lion's Mane, antioxidant activity, and the gut-brain axis</div><p class="study-desc">A summary of how Lion's Mane polysaccharides support antioxidant pathways and influence the gut-brain axis through prebiotic activity.</p><span class="study-arrow">Read on PubMed &rarr;</span></a>
      </div>
    </section>

